You can achieve this by setting specific properties on your OData model to only update the desired fields. Here is an example code snippet to demonstrate this:

```javascript
// Assuming you have an Input control in your form bound to an OData model
<Input value="{path: 'YourEntity>/FieldNameToBeUpdated'}"/>

// Get the model and the binding for the input field
var oModel = this.getView().getModel();
var oBinding = this.getView().byId("YourInputFieldId").getBinding("value");

// Set the property 'useBatchRequests' to false to prevent all changes from being submitted at once
oModel.setUseBatch(false);

// Submit the specific field change to the backend
oBinding.setValue("NewValue");
oModel.submitChanges({
    success: function() {
        console.log("Field updated successfully");
    },
    error: function(oError) {
        console.error("Error updating field: " + oError);
    }
});
```

In this code snippet, we set the property `useBatchRequests` of the OData model to false to prevent all changes from being submitted at once. Then, we update the value of the input field and call `submitChanges()` on the model to send only that specific field update to the backend.

Make sure to replace `'YourEntity>/FieldNameToBeUpdated'` with the appropriate binding path and replace `'YourInputFieldId'` with the actual ID of your input field.

