If you are using two-way binding in SAPUI5, the updated values are automatically recorded in the `changedEntities` of the OData model. In this case, you can directly access the `changedEntities` property of the OData model to filter out the fields that have been updated and submit only those changes to the backend.

Here is an example code snippet to demonstrate this:

```javascript
// Get the OData model
var oModel = this.getView().getModel();

// Set 'useBatchRequests' property to false to prevent all changes from being submitted at once
oModel.setUseBatch(false);

// Get the list of entities that have been updated
var aChangedEntities = oModel.getChangedEntities();

// Loop through the changed entities
aChangedEntities.forEach(function(sEntityPath) {
    var oChangedEntity = oModel.getProperty("/" + sEntityPath);

    // Check which fields of the entity have been updated
    if (oChangedEntity.FieldName1 || oChangedEntity.FieldName2 || oChangedEntity.FieldName3) {
        // Submit the changes to the backend
        oModel.submitChanges({
            success: function() {
                console.log("Changes submitted successfully for entity: " + sEntityPath);
            },
            error: function(oError) {
                console.error("Error submitting changes for entity: " + sEntityPath + " - " + oError);
            }
        });
    }
});
```

In this code snippet, we access the `changedEntities` of the OData model and loop through the entities that have been updated. We then check which fields of the entity have been updated (in this case, `FieldName1`, `FieldName2`, and `FieldName3`), and submit the changes only for those fields.

Make sure to replace `FieldName1`, `FieldName2`, and `FieldName3` with the actual field names that you want to submit.

