You're correct, the `CustomScrollView` cannot be used directly inside an `IntrinsicHeight` widget. To work around this, you can wrap the `CustomScrollView` inside a `SliverFillRemaining` widget, which will take up as much space as needed, but no more than what is available. Here is an example code:

```dart
Column(
  children: [
    // First child takes up as much space as needed
    Text(
      'This is the first child',
      style: TextStyle(fontSize: 20),
    ),
    // Second child takes up the remaining space, without scrolling
    Expanded(
      child: CustomScrollView(
        slivers: [
          SliverFillRemaining(
            hasScrollBody: false,
            child: Column(
              children: [
                // add your widgets here
              ],
            ),
          ),
          // add more sliver widgets if needed
        ],
      ),
    ),
  ],
);
```

In this example, the `Expanded` widget lets the `CustomScrollView` widget take up the remaining space of the `Column` without scrolling. The `SliverFillRemaining` widget allows the inner `Column` widget to fill up the remaining space without expanding beyond it. The `hasScrollBody` property in `SliverFillRemaining` is set to false to prevent the `Column` widget from being scrollable.

